column168: Description Of Events

On Monday 8/1/22, at approx. 6:30 P.M. CDT, Clean Harbors was contacted by Union Pacific Rail personnel to advise that we had a rail car that was leaking an unknown Hazardous Material. Union Pacific Rail personnel contacted United Professional Services (UPS) to respond and clean/remediate the rail tank car. UPS personnel determined that the material was being released from the manway of the rail car and was Raw Gas Oil. The cause of the release was a faulty gasket between the chime of the manway and the lid. UPS personnel replaced the gasket and secured the manway. UPS personnel advised that the manway was properly closed/torqued when they opened the manway to determine the cause of the release. They determined by use of a strapping chart that the total amount released was approx. 5 gal. The remediation efforts generated a 5 gallon bucket of soiled absorbent pads and microbial solution to clean the side of the rail car. This waste material will be manifested and shipped to a final disposal location by United Professional Services. No product was released to the ground.
column169: Clean Harbors Environment Services Inc. will provide remedial training to the affected personnel at the generating / offering facility regarding thorough inspection of the gasket material between the manway chime and the lid of the tank car prior to properly closing the manway per the tank car manufacturer's specific closure instructions. This inspection will be conducted to identify any possible defects in the gasket material that may allow the release of material from the rail car while in transit. If defects are identified, the gasket will be replaced immediately before the tank car is offered for transport.

column168: On August 1, 2022, one (1) 275-gallon tote of NA1760 (contains sodium hydroxide) released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer floor due to an improperly installed cap. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to perform the necessary corrective actions. TLE personnel utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted surface, then transferred the remaining virgin product to a new 275-gallon tote and containerized all sodium hydroxide impacted material into one (1) 5-gallon pail.

When unloading freight from trailer forklift operator picked up freight that had freight stacked on top of it. When doing so the top freight fell over causing the bottom freight to flip backwards and when doing so they pallet the bottom freight was staged on cracked and punctured one of the pails contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured pail.
column169: Forklift operators should move top freight first when unloading freight to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 51 LBS PER SQ INCH EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column168: While unloading a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility located in Fredericksburg, VA an employee discovered a 551A2 with a small hole in the bottom. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 51 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST.
LOOSE LID INSIDE CARTON CLEAN UP AND DISPONED OF IN HOUSE

column168: Container loaded with 10 pallets of batteries with improper blocking and bracing had a load shift and damaged 21  batteries resulting in an estimated 10 gallons of battery acid releasing inside the container and onto the ground.  The blocking and bracing consisted of only 2x6's and a piece of plywood at the rear door.  There was approximately 1' between the end of the pallets and the bracing with no pallet cleats. column169: Ensure proper blocking and bracing before releasing into transportation

column168: On August 8, 2022, at 2145 ET, XPO Logistics experienced a UN1791 “WSI Bleach 12.5% release from a 330 gallon poly tote due to a puncture. No soils, drains, or waterways were reported to have been impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched GrayMar Environmental Services to conduct all onsite cleanup operations.  On August 9, 2022, at 0019 ET, GrayMar personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 60 gallons of product released to a 50’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and asphalt lot. The remaining product in the damaged tote was transferred out and into a new one. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas and collected. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into (3) 55 gallon metal drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 08/18/2022, at 1722 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered GATX70394, a loaded tank car of 2-EthylHexyl Acrylate Inhibited, leaking from under the protective housing. The car was isolated and BASF, IDEM, and NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC Report # 2022-0818-00366. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from the liquid line under the unsecure less then tool tight secondary plug, additionally 4 of 4 blind flange bolts securing the liquid valve to the pressure plate were found less then tool tight. The liquid line valve handle was in the closed position. Hepaco also found a securement pin on a second protective housing broke. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Michael Doring, 225-339-2585, michael.doring@basf.com. Contractor personnel secured the secondary plug, tightened four liquid line flange bolts, secured the protective housing pin on the secondary compartment, and remediated the free standing liquid. The leak was secured a filtered air blanket was placed on the tank and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move and will require a 7.1 report.   Cause Code: 118 NARRI: 5
column169: (NAR CODE: 242 5 What Failed: Liquid Line / Liquid Valve Where Failed: Connection between liquid line and closure (blind) flange Why Failed: Closure (blind) flange bolts/nuts - less than tool tight)  Proper loading procedures and inspections prior to releasing cars into transportation were communicated with the shipper.  Pertaining to this particular car I have recommended that the certificate of construction be reviewed to ascertain if a secondary protective housing is warranted as there were no valves or fittings under the protective housing which mislead first responders to think the car was a multiple compartment car.

column168: During the loading process at the origin terminal the dockworker misjudged the position of their forks on the forklift and punctured a 275 gallon plastic tote. The tote was immediately turned to prevent further release and isolated until a hazmat team could safely transfer the contents into a new container. The released material was neutralized and collected with absorbent material and placed in an overpack for appropriate disposal.
column169: The incident may have been prevented had the employee been more aware of their fork position and surroundings. This employee was counselled on proper forklift operating practices as per company policy. This incident may be used as an example in future dock training topics to show the importance of proper freight handling techniques.

Box 19- Due to it being vapor and not knowing exactly when the release started. The released amount is unquantifiable.   The valve has been plugged and is no longer releasing vapors. We will schedule the car to be inspected and repaired.

column168: SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE CAME TO QA AREA WET AND LEAKING AND WAS PUT INTO A RED TOTE. IT WAS PUT ASIDE FROM THE OTHER PACKAGES. DescribePack: LEAKING FROM THE UP OF THE BOTTLE AROUND THE NECK AREA. THE REASON FOR THE LEAKING WAS A LOOSE CAP ON THE BOTTLE. 2.5 GAL BOTTLE. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PUT INTO A RED TOTE WITH A BAG AND LID ON IT. TAKEN BACK TO THE HAZMAT TO BE PROCESSED.

SequenceEvent: HAZMAT was brought to QA from unload as it was leaking. On inspection, the box was wet but not otherwise damaged. Internal contents consisted of 4 1-gallon bottles, one of which presented with a loose lid. Inadequate packing was noted by lack of internal partitions and/or padding over lids. This absence of padding/protection contributed to release of contents. HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin and then processed as a damage. DescribePack: Package failed as the lid became disconnected and contents were released secondary to lack of padding and protection. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Placed in a lined bin and processed as a damage.

column168: SequenceEvent: The box was transported from the truck to a tugger cart and the package handler noticed it had a small wet spot on the bottom.  A manager notified QA and it was put into an hazmat tub. It was then taken to the hazmat cage. DescribePack: The bottle was cracked towards the top close to the neck.  There was insufficient packing material to keep the bottle from moving in the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box was put in a hazmat tub.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE CAME OUT OF THE TRAILER VISIBLY WET. BROUGHT TO QA CAGE FOR INSPECTION. DescribePack: FOUND THAT THE LID WAS LOOSE AND LEAKED A VERY SMALL AMOUNT. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PLACED PACKAGE IN A HAZMAT BAG AND THEN A HAZMAT TOTE

SequenceEvent: Wet pkg found and placed in a lined Hazmat tote that taken to the Hazmat Processing Area for inspection and damage reporting. DescribePack: Loose caps and failed inner seals allowed liquid to leak wetting and contaminating the contents and carton. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Pkg placed in lined Hazmat tote.

SequenceEvent: Package came damaged in trailer during unload sortation DescribePack: inner packaging came with loose lid causing internal leaking DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: package was placed in QA hazmat cage

SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED WHEN IT GOT TO OUR STATION, THE BOTTOM OF THE PKG WAS OPEN AND LEAKING FLUIDS, THE PKG HANDLERS TOOK IT OUT OF THE TRAILER, CALLED OVER A QA ADIMN TO ACCESS THE PROBLEM, PUT IT IN A RED HAZMAT TOTE, LINED WITH A BLUE PLASTIC HAZMAT BAG TO CATCH ANY LOOSE LIQUID, TOOK IT TO A WELL VENTIALTED AREA TO PROCESS DescribePack: THE PACKAGE DIDN'T HAVE ANY INNER PACKING, THE BOTTOM HALF OF THE BOX WAS WET A TORE FROM THE WETNESS, BOTTLE TOPS WERE NOT SECURED TIGHTLY ENOUGH DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: THE HAZMAT WAS PUT IT IN A RED HAZMAT TOTE, LINED WITH A BLUE PLASTIC HAZMAT BAG TO CATCH ANY LOOSE LIQUID, TOOK IT TO A WELL VENTIALTED AREA TO WRK THE DAMAGES ON IT

SequenceEvent: Package was found by a package handler in trailer 459023. Package was removed from trailer and placed in a plastic bag to prevent further leakage. Upon inspection, it was apparent that the package was loaded on it's side, with the orientation arrows facing horizontally. DescribePack: The lid did not appear to be damaged, but allowed liquid to pass through. The plastic tape around the lid was wet, and there was some liquid in the plastic bag holding the bottle. Most of the leakage was on the bottom and sides of the box. There were no cracked or holes apparent on the bottle. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was immediately turned to the correct orientation, placed in to a plastic bag, then a lined plastic tote.

SequenceEvent: Package was found by QA during the preload sort and declared damaged. Put inside hazmat liner and red tote to stop spilling. MSDS report obtained by shipper. SCMS was processed. Then taken to the hazmat processing cage and put inside a yellow bin. Total duration 1 hour. DescribePack: The lid from the bottle was loose and the liquid spilled DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Hazmat was immediately grabbed by qualified QA and put inside a red lined tote and processed.

SequenceEvent: Received from Unload side. Package was leaking inside a trailer. Package was opened and found with broken cap, not sealed properly. Package was unable to deliver, status codes were applied for customer update. DescribePack: Package was leaking due to broken cap. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was place inside of a salvage drum

SequenceEvent: damaged hazmat received inbound scan this morning, then was brought over to the damage area at an unspecified point in time. discovery date is when HESS and HAP specialists found the package in the damage area. It was already in a lined tote. we moved it over to the drain mats in the incoming damaged hazmat/LQ area. in-house cleanup, awaiting disposition. DescribePack: head of drum along rim on one side has major dent, from which the product leaks when tipped that direction. insufficient information regarding what happened, but the drum most likely fell over or was dropped. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: drum kept upright, placed in lined tote, moved to drain mats

SequenceEvent: driver left a bin with the damaged hazmat on a cart in the front . unclear as to how the damage occurred other than it spilled on the van-presumably fell off the shelf DescribePack: lid became loose DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: placed in bin

SequenceEvent: Package was found leaking. Upon investigation 1 of 2 containers had a loose cap. DescribePack: Loose cap. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a tote and bag to contain the spill.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: SequenceEvent: Package was found to be leaking a gold pigment from the corners of the box. The package was placed in a lined hazardous materials spill containment tote. The package was then brought to the station hazmat cage for further processing. DescribePack: One jar of product had broken during shipment causing gold pigment to spill. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Placed package in a lined spill containment tote and placed in station hazmat cage.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: SequenceEvent: At 8:30am Package handler was moving box from rollers to Work area, package was leaking onto package handlers hands, damage was reported to manager. Manager took action to have package handler wash hands, Package was put into Hazmat bag and put into tote and set was aside for Hazmat certified QA to inspect. DescribePack: upon inspection of Hazmat, it was found that 1-1 Liter container had a loose cap and leaked into and through bag it was contained. DurationRel: 5 and MitigateEffect: Package was put into Hazmat bag and put into tote and set was aside for Hazmat certified QA to inspect. Package was in container that contained an absorbent.

SequenceEvent: On 8-3-22, my supervisor informed me to check a damaged HazMat package that was in the QA HazMat cage. The package was coded a 39 on 8-2-22. The damaged package was inside a blue plastic HazMat bag that was inside a red HazMat container. Upon inspection, I found that the HazMat was inside a plastic container that had a lid that appeared secure. The lid was also taped, with plastic tape, to the container. However, upon tilting the plastic container, I found it to leak from underneath the lid, near the left handle. Approximately, 3 ounces had leaked from the plastic container onto the package bottom. No damage was observed on the plastic container or the outer package.  The package had the upright arrows, but it had to be turned upside down at some point for it to leak. Pictures were taken and all required reports will be filled. DescribePack: The package was leaking from underneath the lid, near the left handle. The lid was also taped to the container with plastic tape, but it still leaked. No damage, holes, or cracks were observed on container. The container only leaked when tilted. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The HazMat package was placed inside a blue plastic Hazmat bag which was then placed inside a red plastic Hazmat container. The package was positioned in an upright position to avoid further spillage.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was moving along conveyer belt when package handler noticed leaking product. Package was brought to QA staging area. Product was slow to spill out of shipping container and almost unnoticed by QA team. Upon further inspection, discovered that the plastic pail inside the box was cracked and spilling product. DescribePack: Exterior cardboard packaging had product slowly spill out the seams of the box. Plastic pail had a 5 inch long crack near the bottom of the pail, curving up and to the left from the bottom of the pail. Product was spilling from this crack into the cardboard shipping container. A large pile of product was surrounding the plastic pail in the bottom of the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Damaged product placed in a blue bag, which in turn was placed in a locking yellow bin for sending to proper disposal location. Any spilled product was carefully swept into the the bag as well.

column168: Kemira's Independent Carrier (TDK Fuller Trucking) was traveling south bound on I95 when the right lane that he was in turned into Exit ramp 53. The driver thought that he was in the lane that continued straight, not the lane that turned into an exit ramp. The driver could not slow down fast enough to make the turn. He locked up the brakes and the truck and trailer rolled on its side. About 4-5 gallons of product leaked from the dome lid as the trailer was on its side. About 2 more gallons leaked while emergency responders were in the process of getting the product pumped out of the trailer and into another trailer. Emergency responders drilled holes in the side of the trailer to pump out the product into a backup trailer. Product was contained to about a 5 ft by 5 ft area that was remediated. Excavators were on site to clean up any contaminated soil.
column169: Equipment was in proper condition. Accident occurred due to driver error. Driver admitted to travelling too fast for being in the wrong lane. Driver's lease agreement with Kemira is being cancelled as a result of the incident.

column168: On August 03, 2022, Landstar called to request assistance for a 5-gallon release of Sodium hydroxide, solution cleaning products by Ecolab impacting the inside of trailer 755440 and underneath the trailer. Only media affected consisted of the trailer components and underlying asphalt, no soil or waterways were impacted.  Waste is currently pending disposal.

column168: On August 10, 2022 at 1335 ET, Landstar contacted ERTS regarding a UN1263, Paint, 3, PG II release that occurred inside of a trailer at Petro, 1295 Horizon Blvd., Socorro, TX. ERTS dispatched a contractor to perform the clean up and assess the impacted areas.  Graymar arrived onsite and located the release, they confirmed only one gallon had released on to the trailer floor due to a puncture from a nail in a pallet.  Graymar used absorbents on the affected areas of the trailer.  One 55-gallon DM was generated containing the damaged pail and impacted absorbents.  Waste is still pending disposal.

On 08/27/22, at 0730, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard, noted a line of tank cars which included TILX402124, a residue tank car of Acetaldehyde, possibly emitting a vapor odor from the protective housing. The car was isolated and Vertellus Integrated, NRC, and IDEM were notified.  CHEMTREC#2022-0827-00107. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line secondary plug less then tool tight, and the vapor line valve open approximately 1/8 inch. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Kathy Amick 317-417-6045. Contractor personnel closed the vapor line and secured the secondary plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. No, 7.1 is required.  Cause Code: 136 NARRI: 5
column169: (NAR code 136) Shipper was contacted and advised to check loading procedures and conduct remedial training with loading handlers.

column168: On August 11, 2022, Landstar called ERTS to report a propane tank that holds 500 gallons had a leaking valve.  No storm drains or waterways were impacted. A contractor was dispatched to the site.  Basin Environmental arrived onsite along with Amerigas who brought a crane to move the tanks so the contractor would be able to tighten the leaking valve. One tank was located by Amerigas who confirmed it was the valve leaking which was tightened by themselves and no other tanks were damaged or leaking. Basin Environmental departed the site and no waste was generated.
Oregon DOT Hazmat inspector reported a release from tankcar, the vacuum relief valve was found to be leaking, vapor from the threads.

column168: NM State Hazmat Inspector identified CELX 23213 as leaking while in the Clovis yard.  The car was isolated and BNSF Hazmat responder inspected the car finding a small leak coming from the liquid line flange below the valve.  2 of 4 bolts were loose and tightened approximately 1 full turn each to stop the leak.  Hazmat Hold placed on the car and shipper notified to request OTMA 1 for movement to destination for offloading and shop for repair/testing.  All spilled material evaporated from the car body with no ground impacts.

column168: On 08/18/2022 LARS received notification from Hub personnel that unit UPGZ 511908 was observed leaking after the unit was deramped from the railcar at the San Bernardino Intermodal Facility. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed inside of the containment pit pending a cargo inspection. Environmental contractor (United Pumping) was dispatched to perform a cargo inspection and to remediate the leaking product along with the affected areas. Interior inspection revealed mixed freight varying in sizes and weights, stacked multiple layers high throughout the container, 3 DID airbags were found deflated and dislodged at the rear of the load no other forms of load securement were applied on this shipment which is required per the BNSF Intermodal Rules and Policies Guide. A metal container containing a purple paint related material was found to be the source of the leak, it has been determined the leak was caused by a failed/loose seal on the lid of the container. Contractor was able to remediate the spill and affected areas. The shipment was reloaded / secured with seal 27670428

column168: Hub Group Trucking called to request assistance with an unknown amount of of an unknown hazardous liquid release on trailer at location in Patterson, CA. column168: A Veolia employee was off loading a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility in Azusa, CA.  The trailer contained a pallet of containers stretched wrapped together on a pallet. The employee proceeded to remove this pallet with a forklift and while he was attempting to the lift the pallet the forks of the forklift punctured the container. This action resulted in a release of the contents of a single 3 gallon poly closed top container. The forklift operator immediately noticed the release and proceeded to clean up the spill along with other hazmat trained Veolia employees. All spilled material was absorbed with absorbent pads and powder and was repacked into a new 5 gallon container.   The cause of the spill was due to broken planks on the pallet which allowed the bottoms of the 3 gallon poly containers to sag below the top deckboard. When the forklift operator placed his forks inside the opening and lifted the pallet, the container got punctured. The entire duration of the spill was less than 1 minute due to the container size.
column169: Veolia will retrain its employees to examine wooden pallets prior to off-loading to keep an eye out for any signs of broken or compromised pallets, such as containers that are not uniform or leaning which could be an indicator of potential broken deckboards.

The tank had returned to the yard with approximately 400 gallons of Waste Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic n.o.s. (Sulfuric Acid) 8, PG II on Friday 8/19/2022. On 8/20/2022 it was discovered that material had leaked onto the pavement. The material was cleaned up immediately and inspection of the valve revealed that the valve may not have properly seated and there was not a gasket in the cap to prevent liquid from leaking. Vacuum was applied to the tank and the valve was opened and closed a few times to ensure the valve closed properly. These actions worked and there was no additional release of the material. The material was transferred into totes and transported for disposal.
column169: Additional training regarding conducting safety inspections of piping, valves, hoses and caps will be provided to team members. The cargo tank has been sent for required tests and inspections.

column25: Odjfell Terminals Houston A/O KRATON POLYMERS US LLC
column168: On 08/07/2022, at 1731 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered UTLX 952520, a loaded tank car of Isoprene, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper of record, National Response Center, and West Virginia DEP were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0807-00047). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor valve operating handle partially open and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Pat Mentzel of Odjfell Terminals, phone 832-359-1557. Contractor personnel closed the operating valve and installed the secondary closure plug in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 136 NARRI:100
column169: (NAR Code: 136 vapor line valve open, plug not secure)

column168: On 08/12/2022, at 0828 hours, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Terminal discovered SOEX 2827, a residue tank car of Hydrocarbons, Liquid, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper of record, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0812-00133). HEPACO, LLC, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an active leak from the bottom outlet valve operating handle packing gland. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the consignee, Tim Langford of Shell. Contractor personnel secured the release by tightening the bottom outlet valve packing gland nut. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 533 NARRI: 40
column169: (NAR code:533 2 What Failed: Stuffing Box for Bottom Outlet Valve Where Failed: Cover of stuffing box Why Failed: Loose packing gland nut)

On August 4, 2022, at 0920 ET, Metropolitan Trucking Inc. reported multiple products released inside the back of the trailer floor due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to perform all clean up operations. On August 4, 2022, at 1105 ET, EnviroServe arrived on site and confirmed the following products released: - ZEP, High pH presoak vehicle wash- (1)5 gallon bucket- 2.5 gal.  - ZEP, Touchless Foaming car and truck detergent – (3) 5 gallon buckets- 12 gal.  - ZEP, Formula 22- (2) 5 gallon buckets- 10 gal.  - ZEP, FS Cooler freezer cleaner- (2) 5 gallon buckets, 10 gal.  - ZEP, Sili Free- (4) 5 gallon buckets- 20 gal.   EnviroServe removed all impacted pails from the trailer, utilized granular absorbents on impacted areas, collected and containerized damaged pails, spent absorbents into (5) 55-gallon poly drums and (1) 20-gallon poly drum. All waste was transported offsite for disposal.

SequenceEvent: HAZMAT was dropped while being loaded and began leaking. QA was called to inspect the damage. On evaluation, the HAZMAT was leaking and the box was wet and crushed. DescribePack: HAZMAT failed when it was dropped, which crushed  a portion of the box and one of the four bottles corresponding to that area. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: HAZMAT was placed in a lined bin and processed as a damage.

SequenceEvent: A scent was noticed coming from the package and it was taken aside for inspection. Upon seeing the damage, it was set in the hazmat area for processing. The bag was well sealed and is holding the fluids. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: The box was set aside into the hazmat processing area, away from other packages.

SequenceEvent: Inner pkg was damaged at the destination then placed in an unmarked salvage drum and sent to the wrong Hub for evaluation/disposal. DescribePack: There is a 1/4" cut/hole on the bottom edge of the 1 x 5 gal container which allowed liquid to leak when placed upright in the salvage drum. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Initial discovery location placed the container with a hole on the bottom upright in the salvage drum which allowed it to continue leaking. Upon discovery at this location the container was removed from the salvage drum, ensured cap was tight and secure before turning the damaged pkg upside down to mitigate the release. Pkg was placed in a new lined Hazmat salvage drum to await disposition and prepare for disposal.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was placed inside of red hazmat tote and given to QA for processing. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed inside of hazmat tote inside of tote liner and placed inside the hazmat cage thereafter.

SequenceEvent: the bottle of acetone had a loose cap. at some point in transit it became so loose that the majority of the acetone leaked out. we stored the hazmat in accordance with the SDS in the hazmat cage and later on we entered a DPR, ISF and began the HESS entry for disposition. DescribePack: loose cap DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: made sure no one was around and made sure it was a fully vented area.

SequenceEvent: Package was unloaded off Ecolab trailer with other hazmats. Immediately the issue was noticed as it looked to be a dried substance that had dripped from the rim. The package was then set aside in the QA area for further processing. DescribePack: There was a slight lip in the lid which caused for a faulty seal. The lip appeared to have been caused by something getting stuck underneath the lid itself & then had pressure applied as if someone were trying to open the contents. The lip is about 1 inch in diameter. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was secured in a well ventilated area to await further processing.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: At 0724 ET, XPO terminal XLA in La Salle, IL, reported a spill/leak that occurred inside trailer #4638285 at approximately 0700 ET. The spill consisted of 1 or more 773 pound steel cylinders of argon refrigerated liquid, which was discovered by a dock worker as they heard a "hissing" sound coming from the trailer. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct a site assessment and cleanup. At 1042 ET, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite. Hepaco observed a cylinder of Argon that had been overfilled or became overpressurized due to ambient temperature change. Once the unit reached 350 PSI, the safety relief valve allows the Argon to escape and reduce pressure in the vessel. However, the relief unit is spring operated and once the unit froze, the valve was stuck in the open position. ERTS contacted the shipper and they confirmed this was a common occurrence and advised that if necessary, leave the unit outside and open the vent line and release the material. Hepaco ultimately applied warm water to the ice that had formed which allowed the relief valve to close and stop releasing. ERTS asked Hepaco to check the pressure on the other two cylinders of Argon in this shipment. Hepaco reported that they were close to 350 PSI and agreed to release some of the pressure so all three units could ship on without further incident. No waste was generated.

column168: On August 22, 2022 at 0833 ET, Landstar contacted ERTS  to request spill response for a reported UN1993 cargo release.  Following contractor arrival and assessment of the involved cargo, it was determined that only a single tote was leaking from a “BB” sized puncture toward the bottom of the leaking tote. No other totes were observed to be leaking. Based on the location of the puncture, which was not able to be punctured or rubbed by adjacent cargo, the contractor could not determine the cause of the puncture. The tote contents were subsequently transferred into a “new” tote and absorbent was spread over the 20ft by 5ft area of concrete that was impacted.  Once the crew completed operations it was determined that an estimated 95 gallons had been released to the concrete lot. The crew collected and containerized the absorbents into the damaged tote and departed the site with waste until proper disposal.

column168: On August 24, 2022 at 1727 ET, Landstar contacted ERTS to request spill response for an unknown amount of UN3264 Enthone - Viaform Make-Up LA on trailer # 668790. Green Site Services Group (GSS) arrived on site at 2200 EST to assess the impacted areas.  A photo of the cause of damage to the drum was not able to be done since it was already overpacked, but the terminal manager informed GSS that there was a small nail puncture on the bottom. GSS was able to indicate that 2 gallons of UN3264, Corrosive Liquids, Acidic, Inorganic, N.O.S (Sulphuric Acid/Copper Sulphate) had leaked from one 55-gallon DF. One 55-gallon poly drum was damaged and was already overpacked into a 95-gallon poly drum. Terminal personnel also generated a 55-gallon metal drum of absorbents, GSS overpacked the metal drum into a 95-gallon poly drum. 2 gallons of product spilled in total under the trailer in a 1ft by 3ft area as well as a 4ft by 4ft area. GSS unloaded and confirmed no other drums were damaged but two pallets were impacted.  A soda ash solution was used to neutralize the impacted areas. Before the crew departed the site one additional 55-gallon poly drum containing impacted pallets and absorbents was generated.  GGS departed the site with all waste to properly dispose of.

column168: At 0948 Hours, the Brittain Yard Switch Crew noticed tank car TILX 112425 fuming from the top of the car and having a strong odor.  They called the Brittain Yard Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE to come out and investigate.  When I arrived, I saw that fumes were coming from the fill port and that product was running down the right side of the car.  I called Enviroserve out of Canton, OH to come out and mitigate the leak and clean the side of the car along with a small area of ground that had been contaminated from the leaking product. They arrived and removed seal number CM10768 from the fill port lid and when they opened the lid, they found that the gasket was off center, causing the leak.  The gasket was in good condition so they centered the gasket on the fill port hole and closed and secured the lid.  Enviroserve then installed new seals 4255514,4255541,4255510,4255515 and 4255516.  After installing new seals, they cleaned the spilled product from inside of the protective housing and wiped down the right side of the car.  They also neutralized the discolored stone on the ground where the product spilled.  The car was then released for service at 1600 hrs.
column169: More attention needs paid to the gasket placement before closing the lid of the fill port.

column168: Driver was at truck stop and noticed Ieakage from rear of trailer. He called his dispatcher and my company, Environmental Management, Inc.(EMI) was contacted to provide a response. I called Graymar Environmental(GE) and requested a crew respond. Upon arrival, GE made entry into the enclosed trailer and observe one(1) 275-gallon tote was on its side. The tote was in the second row from the rear. There was a total of 16 totes on the load. GE observed the totes in the front had shifted forward and allowed this tote to fall over on its side. There was a bladder inside the outside plastic walls which had burst down one side because of the impact when it fell over. GE removed all the 16 totes, wiped them down, and cleaned the trailer as much as possible. JPS arranged to have a second trailer brought to the site and GE loaded the 15 undamaged totes onto this trailer. GE removed the damaged tote and all other cleanup debris and transported it to their terminal. Estimated time of the release was 3-4 hours. GE was at the site for at least 24 hours monitoring the area after the cleanup was complete and the second trailer was obtained to load the undamaged totes.

column168: A piece of luggage was offered by the shipper. Customs spot checked this shipment and opened it. Among the contents were included two 400 g metal aerosol cans of antiperspirant with flammable Globally Harmonized System (GHS) pictograms. The manufacturer's safety data sheet indicates that the correct identification/classification is UN 1950, Aerosols flammable, division 2.1, flammable gas. These had been held in customs for some time before FedEx Express was notified in UAE. DG Administration was made aware of this incident on 8/10/22. As the shipper had not offered the shipment with any DG marks, labels nor a shipper's declaration it is undeclared/hidden DG. The competent authority in United Arab Emirates was notified by local personnel in UAE, Reporting Dangerous Goods Occurrence (RODGO) number 0003255122 to the UAE General Civil Aviation Authority. I notified FAA via their email process and photos were sent on 8/10. Once released by the competent authority in UAE the DG will be removed from the luggage for local environmental disposal in order for the remainder of the package to be delivered.

column168: On August 3, 2022, ERTS was contacted by Landstar personnel in Laredo, Texas requesting facilitation of the cleanup of a trailer impacted by spilled paint.  ERTS then dispatched contractors to manage all onsite cleanup activities.  Following contractor arrival and assessment of the involved cargo, it was determined that approximately three (3) gallons of W111 Waterbased Coating (Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, n.o.s., Marine Pollutant (Zinc Oxide), UN3082) spilled from a crack at the bottom of the involved container that was presumed to have been caused as the result of “stress” from overhead weight caused by a load shift. Contractors cleaned up the release using absorbents, hand tools and the proper PPE.  The damaged pail, spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (1) 55-gallon plastic drum. The waste drum was then transported by the contractor to US Ecology disposal facility in Robstown, Texas for proper disposal.

Spill was cleaned as well as possible and package was placed in a steel salvage drum pending FAA investigation and package.

column168: A MEMPHIS SPILL AGENT WAS CALLED TO THE DANGEROUS GOODS BUILDING FOR A LEAKING SHIPMENT. THE AGENT RECEIVED A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING A UN1263 THAT HAD A BLACK LIQUID COMING FROM THE BOTTOM CORNER OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. EMPLOYEE IN THE DANGEROUS GOODS BUILDING TOLD THE AGENT THAT THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN DROPPED DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. WHILE INVESTIGATING THE SHIPMENT THE AGENT FOUND THAT THE METAL JERRYCAN INSIDE HAD A DAMAGED BOTTOM CORNER. THIS CAUSED THE SEAM TO OPEN AND RELEASE ITS CONTENTS INSIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A STEEL SALVAGE PACKAGE AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR AN AMENDED SHIPPERS DECLARATION.

The cargo tank remained intact. The cargo tank was reinforced by Abs, some of which were damaged. No product was released from the cargo tank.
